
[1]estrange

   ESTRANGE, v.t.

   1. To keep at a distance; to withdraw; to cease to frequent and be
   familiar with.

   Had we estranged ourselves form them in things indifferent.

   I thus estrange my person from her bed.

   2. To alienate; to divert from its original use or possessor; to apply
   to a purpose foreign from its original or customary one.

   They have estranged this place, and burnt incense in it to other gods.
   Jer.19.

   3. To alienate, as the affections; to turn from kindness to
   indifference or malevolence.

   I do not know, to this hour, what it is that has estranged him from me.

   4. To withdraw; to withhold.

   We must estrange our belief from what is not clearly evidenced.
